# **3\. Thermal Analyses and Certification**

## **3.1 Scope of Project**

### 3.1.1 Problem

In the CubeSat’s orbital environment, it is  exposed to extreme and rapidly varying thermal conditions as it alternates between sunlight and eclipse. These temperature fluctuations pose a significant risk to sensitive electronics onboard the CubeSat, which may fail if exposed to temperatures beyond their survival temperature limits, jeopardising mission success. While thermal solutions such as heaters and heat sinks can mitigate these risks, the CubeSat’s limited space and power require any solution must be highly optimised. Hence, an in-depth understanding of orbital environments and the CubeSat’s thermal performance and capabilities is required.

### 3.1.2 Objectives

There are 3 main objectives:

1. Understanding of the Orbital environment  
   * Hottest and coldest temperatures in Sunlit & Eclipse phases  
   * Hot / cool spots within the   
2. Design of thermal control systems  
   * Heating / cooling effects due to different CubeSat orientations with respect to the Sun and Earth  
   * Quantification of heaters / heat sin  
3. Validate CubeSat thermal performance

### 3.1.3 Current Progress

The work that has been completed includes understanding of the mission’s thermal requirements and the respective subsystems’ thermal limits. I am currently in the midst of building thermal models and conducting simulations, and have obtained certain conclusive results about the temperature range of the CubeSat.

In Sem 2, the work will come in 2 parts to work towards thermal validation:

1. Continual refinement of the Thermal model & CAD  
2. Testing of proposed solutions

## **3.2 Design (Thermal) Specifications**

### 3.2.1 Orbital Environment

Orbital Parameters:

- CubeSat size: 6U (30cm x 20cm x 10cm)  
- Altitude: 550km  
- Type: Sun \- Synchronous Orbit, 98° inclination  
- Period: 96 min orbit, 62min Sunlit phase and 34min Eclipse phase

External Heat Inputs:

1. Direct solar radiation:  
   * Solar constant: 1361 W/m²  
   * Present only during the Sunlit phase, as direct line of sight to the Sun is required  
   * Primary source of heat gain throughout the orbital cycle  
2. Earth Albedo (reflected solar radiation):  
   * Earth Albedo coefficient: 0.31  
   * Reflected flux \= 0.31 \* 1361 \= \~422 W/m²  
   * Present only during the Sunlit phase  
   * Affects Earth-facing surfaces of the CubeSat due to reflection of the Sun’s solar radiation from Earth’s surface and atmosphere  
3. Earth Infrared (IR) emission:  
   * Flux of \~ 230 W/m²  
   * Emitted continuously from Earth’s surface and atmosphere  
   * Present through both Sunlit and Eclipse phases, contributing to baseline heating  
   * Affects Earth-facing surfaces at all times

External Heat sinks:

1. Deep space background radiation:  
   * Effective ambient Space temperature: 3K  
   * Acts as a constant heat sink, causing radiative cooling from all exposed surfaces of the CubeSat

### 3.2.2 Mission phases

This CubeSat operates in 4 distinct phases, each defined by different operational modes and corresponding thermal environments. Across which, subsystem activity varies.

1. Sunlit Autonomous:  
   * Solar panels set facing the sun for charging  
2. Eclipse Autonomous:  
   * Minimal output to preserve power  
   * Only essential subsystems will be kept on  
3. Sunlit Imaging:  
   * Usage of payload camera, pointed towards Earth for imaging  
4. Eclipse tasking:  
   * Downlinking of data back to Earth via the KU Band

In a 24-hour period, the CubeSat will complete approximately 15 orbits around the Earth. Of which, 13 are autonomous, including both Sunlit and Eclipse, with 1 orbit for Sunlit Imaging, and 1 orbit for Eclipse tasking.

## **3.3 Concept Generation**

A thermal model of the CubeSat was developed using Solidworks to evaluate its temperature behaviour across multiple orbital cycles and mission phases. Thermal parameters were defined by applying boundary heat loads based on the respective orbital phase (Sunlit and Eclipse), factoring in direct solar radiation, Earth albedo, Earth IR and ambient Space temperature. A transient thermal study was conducted to obtain the CubeSat’s temperature changes through the autonomous Sunlit and Eclipse phases. The validity of the results will be verified with industrial partners, and used to guide thermal solutions required.

## **3.5 Simulation tests**

### 3.5.1 Purpose of testing

The primary objective of the thermal simulation at this interim stage is to get approximate values of the temperature range that the CubeSat and its internal components will experience in orbit. It also seeks to discover any hot or cool spots within the CubeSat. The simulations were conducted with parameters as representative as possible of the CubeSat’s sun-synchronous orbit. Only radiative and conductive heat transfer mechanisms were allowed, as convective heat transfer is absent in the vacuum of space. Radiative thermal transfer was modelled using varying heat fluxes applied on the CubeSat’s respective surfaces, for both heat gain due to the Earth and Sun, and heat lost to ambient space temperature.

### 3.5.2 Simulation parameters

The thermal properties of 3 main materials (sourced from SolidWorks’ in-built material library) were applied. Glass was used for the solar panels, epoxy for the PCBs, and aluminium 6061 for the frame and remaining components. The density of the CAD model of each subsystem was also adjusted based on its weight taken from GomSpace’s specification sheets and the corresponding volume of its CAD geometry (obtained from SolidWorks). This approach preserves each subsystem’s mass, ensuring that results of thermal simulations were as accurate as possible.

The applied heat loads varied according to the transient thermal study. Sun facing surfaces (Solar Panels) received 1361 W/m² of heat flux during the Sunlit phase, while Earth facing surfaces (underside of Solar Panels and the bottom of the CubeSat) received 650 W/m² of heat flux during the Sunlit phase and 230 W/m² during Eclipse. Deep Space background radiation to an ambient temperature of 3K was applied to all external surfaces.

### 3.5.3 Simulation methodology

Initial conditions were set at Deep Space’s ambient temperature of 3K, and simulations were repeated under the same conditions until the CubeSat’s temperature profile remained constant. This temperature distribution would represent the thermal conditions of the CubeSat during its autonomous operational phases. The temperature at the end of the Eclipse phase would be the coolest that the CubeSat experiences, and the temperature at the end of the Sunlit phase would roughly be the hottest without additional heaters or heat loads from the mission payloads.

### 3.6.2 Analyses of results

From the results of the thermal simulations of the autonomous phases there are a few critical findings:

1. Components without sufficient continuous power draw will likely require a heating solution  
   * Many subsystems, such as the Simera Camera (main payload), reaches temperatures below \-40°C, far below its minimum operating temperature of \-10°C  
     * Even at the end of the Sunlit phase, the Simera Camera reaches a maximum temperature of \-35°C  
   * SDR and the KU Band comms reach \-30°C, below their respective minimum operating temperatures too  
2. Components with continuous power draw may generate sufficient heat to stay within their operating temperatures  
   * The ADCS and OBC are able stay well within their operating temperature ranges, maintaining at temperatures of 40 to 50°C  
   * The battery and its heater, which reaches a low temperature of \-35°C, is still within its operational temperature range. Given that it can draw power directly from the solar panels during the charging phase, it will be able to produce heat to keep the battery within its operational temperature range. More simulations will need to be done to ascertain this.  
3. Overheating of solar panels  
   * Current simulations show that at the end of the Sunlit Autonomous phase, edges of the solar panels reach temperatures of 170°C, far beyond its operational temperature range of 100°C  
   * It cools to 75°C during the 34min Eclipse phase, showing a rapid rate of heat loss when not in direct sunlight

## **3.7 Current shortcomings and Future work**

### 3.7.1 Current shortcomings

The work presented however, has shortcomings of 2 natures.

Firstly, thermal simulation models in general are far from ideal, and are not fully convincing in certifying a CubeSat for the thermal environment it will experience during orbit. While thermal simulations are an essential work for Thermal certification initially, physical testing of a CubeSat in a Thermal Vacuum is required at a later stage. The biggest difference between SolidWorks simulations and the actual environment is that the rate of change of heat fluxes and power loads are not well accounted for. For example, during the Sunlit autonomous phase, while the solar panels do receive a constant heat flux from the sun, the same cannot be said for other CubeSat surfaces receiving radiation from the Earth. Due to different positions of the CubeSat with respect to the Earth at different parts of the orbit, different surfaces will receive different amounts of heat that is gradually changing.

However, in the current simulation, only the bottom surface of the CubeSat is modelled to be receiving heat from the Earth throughout the simulation. Other surfaces receive no heat from Earth at all, which is definitely not the case. Especially since the bottom surface has the smallest exposed surface area (20cm x 10cm as compared to the sides 30cm x 10cm), the actual temperature of the Cubesat is likely to be higher than shown during the simulation. Although the difference is not expected to be significant, more accurate data will be needed, especially when designing the heating solutions required.

Secondly, while the CubeSat model’s current fidelity is sufficient for getting rough results, it is not fully representative of the heat distribution within Cubesat subsystems. In the current model, each subsystem was set to radiate heat equally across all of its surfaces, hence current simulations show almost uniform temperature throughout each subsystem. However, in reality only certain parts of each subsystem emits heat, thereby each subsystem will likely have its own temperature gradient not shown in the current results. Hence, more work can be done to obtain these results.

### 3.7.2 Future work

Future work to be done shall seek to improve the thermal certification of the CubeSat with higher accuracy. Firstly, the fidelity of the model needs to be continually improved, and adapted in conjunction with the payload and subsystem developments of other CubeSat teams. Additionally, in terms of testing, methods to ensure simulations that are more representative of the actual orbital thermal environment will need to be developed. This will be done through more exchanges with industry partners to understand existing methods in use, as well as to compare my simulation results against actual orbital temperatures of CubeSats that have flown in space to validate my methods. Finally, appropriate heating and cooling (more so heating based on preliminary simulation results and industrial insight) solutions will need to be designed for this CubeSat.
